#week-title("Two", "Purifying the Sulphur by Repeated Distillation")

=== Core Teaching

The Sulphur fraction isolated in Week 1 is not yet in its purest state. It
carries residual Mercury (the more volatile fractions that did not separate
cleanly in the first isolation) and possibly some earthy material that has
been carried across during distillation. Repeated distillation purifies the
Sulphur progressively, removing these residuals at each pass.

*Why this matters philosophically.* The soul principle in any substance — in
a plant, in a mineral, in a human being — is rarely encountered in a pure
state. It is almost always mixed with the volatile spirit (Mercury) that
enlivens it and the fixed body (Salt) that gives it form. The work of
purifying the Sulphur is the work of coming to know the essential character
of a substance beneath all the accidental qualities that surround it. In
inner alchemical terms, this is the work of distinguishing genuine soul-
quality from habituated personality: the difference between what you
essentially are and what you have become through circumstance.

*The process of rectification.* Each distillation of the Sulphur fraction:
1. Removes residual lighter fractions (Mercury) that come over first — these
   are collected separately and returned to the Mercury pool.
2. Concentrates the Sulphur in the middle fraction — the heart of the run.
3. Leaves residual heavier material (semi-fixed Sulphur approaching Salt) in
   the flask residue — this may be combined with the Salt for later cohobation.

After two or three rectifications, the Sulphur fraction is noticeably more
consistent in character: its colour, scent, and viscosity are more stable and
more pronounced. This is the Sulphur approaching its essential nature.

*Comparison after rectification.* Smell the rectified Sulphur alongside the
original isolated fraction. The difference may be subtle or dramatic, depending
on the source preparation. Record it in precise language. This precision of
sensory language is itself a form of alchemical practice — the tradition's
texts are filled with exact descriptions of colour, scent, and texture because
these are the primary diagnostic tools of the craft.

=== Topics This Week

- Rectification: what it accomplishes and why it is necessary
- The rectification sequence: separating Mercury residual, concentrating heart,
  leaving heavy fraction
- The philosophical meaning of purifying the characterising principle
- Developing precise sensory language for preparation characteristics

#inner-work[
  *The Essential vs. the Accidental*

  Contemplate the difference between your essential character (Sulphur
  rectified) and the accidental characteristics that surround it (the
  mixed, unrectified fraction).

  What would remain of your most characteristic self if the habituated patterns,
  the circumstantial responses, and the socially adapted personality were
  distilled away? Record your observations.
]

